Read by Stephen Eley.</p>

<p><i>Two men left.  Franklin D. Roosevelt.  D for Delano, mind.  Governor of New York.  Cousin to Teddy Roosevelt.  Already ran for Vice President once.  Didn&#8217;t win.  Cigarette holder.  Jaunty angle.  Wheelchair.  Paralysis.  Anguish.  Courage.  As near an aristocrat as America grows.  Franklin D. Roosevelt.  D for Delano.</i></p>

<p><i>And Joe Steele.</i></p>

<p><i>Joe Steele.  Congressman from California.  Not San Francisco.  Not Nob Hill.  Good Lord, no.  Fresno.  Farm country.  That great valley, squeezed by mountains east and west.  Not a big fellow, Joe Steele.  Stands real straight, so you don&#8217;t notice too much.  Mustache, a good-sized one.  Thick head of hair just starting to go gray.  Eyelids like shutters.  When they go down and then come up again, you can&#8217;t see what was behind them.
</i></p>

<p><b>Rated R</b>.  Contains profanity and strong political themes.  Not happy politics, like we have today.  1930s politics.</p>

